# System Context Map – Payments Domain

# Purpose

This document describes how the Payments Domain fits into the broader system landscape. It defines bounded contexts, relationships between domains, communication patterns, and integration styles.

It ensures consistent understanding of system interactions and prevents tight coupling between domains.

---

# Context Names

This section defines the bounded contexts interacting with the Payments Domain.

## Core Domains

* Payments Domain (this context)
* Orders Domain
* Customer Domain
* Billing Domain
* Subscription Domain

## Supporting Domains

* Notifications Domain
* Fraud Detection Domain
* Reporting & Analytics Domain

## External Systems

* Payment Service Providers (PSPs)
* Banking Systems
* ERP Systems
* Identity Providers (IdP)

---

# Relationships

## Payments ↔ Orders

* Relationship: Downstream dependency (Orders → Payments initiation)
* Description: Orders initiate payment requests and depend on payment confirmation for fulfillment.

---

## Payments ↔ Billing

* Relationship: Upstream/Downstream (bi-directional integration)
* Description: Billing may trigger payments, and Payments provides settlement results.

---

## Payments ↔ Customer

* Relationship: Reference dependency
* Description: Payments references customer identity but does not own customer data.

---

## Payments ↔ Subscription

* Relationship: Downstream dependency
* Description: Subscription domain triggers recurring payment execution.

---

## Payments ↔ Notifications

* Relationship: Event-driven consumer
* Description: Notifications listens to payment events to inform users of payment status changes.

---

## Payments ↔ Fraud Detection

* Relationship: Event-driven analytical dependency
* Description: Fraud systems consume payment events for risk scoring and anomaly detection.

---

## Payments ↔ External Payment Providers

* Relationship: Integration dependency
* Description: Payments interacts with external PSPs for execution and settlement.

---

## Payments ↔ Reporting & Analytics

* Relationship: Data consumer
* Description: Reporting systems consume payment events and records for business intelligence.

---

# Communication Patterns

## Synchronous Communication

Used when immediate response is required.

### Examples

* Payment initiation request
* Payment validation checks
* Provider authorization calls

### Characteristics

* REST or gRPC APIs
* Low latency requirement
* Strong consistency expectations

---

## Asynchronous Communication

Used for decoupled and scalable interactions.

### Examples

* Payment status updates
* Payment completion events
* Refund notifications

### Characteristics

* Event-driven messaging (Kafka or similar)
* Eventually consistent
* High scalability and resilience

---

## Event-Driven Communication

Core pattern for cross-domain integration.

### Events Published

* PaymentCreated
* PaymentAuthorized
* PaymentProcessing
* PaymentCompleted
* PaymentFailed
* PaymentRefunded

### Consumers

* Notifications
* Fraud Detection
* Reporting
* Analytics
* Customer Support Tools

---

## Request-Response Pattern

Used primarily for internal or external service calls.

### Examples

* Provider payment execution
* Payment status query
* Idempotency validation checks

---

# Integration Styles

## REST APIs

* Used for external system communication
* Standard for payment initiation and queries
* Stateless and request-driven

---

## Event Streaming (Kafka or equivalent)

* Primary integration backbone for domain events
* Used for propagation of payment state changes
* Enables loose coupling between domains

---

## Webhooks

* Used for external PSP callbacks
* Asynchronous provider notifications
* Requires idempotency handling

---

## gRPC (Internal)

* Used for high-performance internal service communication
* Low-latency payment orchestration calls
* Strongly typed contracts

---

## Batch Processing

* Used for reconciliation workflows
* Settlement matching with external providers
* Reporting data synchronization

---

## Database Integration (Avoided)

* Direct database access across domains is strictly prohibited
* All interactions must go through APIs or events

---

# Summary

The Payments Domain operates as a central orchestration and reconciliation hub within the system landscape. It relies on a combination of synchronous APIs for execution-critical flows and asynchronous event-driven communication for scalability, resilience, and cross-domain consistency.

Clear separation of contexts and strict integration boundaries ensure the domain remains loosely coupled, observable, and evolvable over time.
